Yes ✅ — **throttle is exactly the right concept for this scenario**, **but with an important clarification**.

When you have **1 lakh (100,000) records** and you load **30–40 items on scroll**, the **best practice is:**

> **Use THROTTLING for the scroll event + pagination/virtualization for rendering**

Let me explain **clearly**, step‑by‑step, with a **React example**.

***

## 🔴 The Problem You’re Solving

*   You have **100,000 records**
*   You **cannot render all at once** → browser will crash / lag
*   You want to:
    *   Load **30–40 records at a time**
    *   Load more when user scrolls down
*   Scroll event fires **hundreds of times per second**

❌ Without control → too many scroll handler executions  
✅ With throttling → controlled, performant loading

***

## ✅ Where Throttle Fits PERFECTLY

### Throttle is used to:

*   **Limit how often the scroll handler runs**
*   Example: run **once every 300–500ms**, not on every scroll tick

<!---->

    Scroll Event (fires continuously)
    ↓
    Throttle
    ↓
    Check: reached bottom?
    ↓
    Load next 30–40 records

***

## ✅ High‑Level Architecture (Industry Standard)

    Scroll Event
       ↓
    Throttle (300ms)
       ↓
    Check scroll position
       ↓
    If near bottom → loadMore()
       ↓
    Append 30–40 items

***

## ✅ Example: Infinite Scroll using Throttle in React

### ✅ Basic Setup (Mock Data)

```js
const allData = Array.from({ length: 100000 }, (_, i) => `Item ${i + 1}`);
```

***

### ✅ Component with Throttled Scroll

```jsx
import { useState, useEffect, useRef } from "react";
import throttle from "lodash.throttle";

const PAGE_SIZE = 30;

function InfiniteScroll() {
  const [items, setItems] = useState([]);
  const page = useRef(0);

  const loadMore = () => {
    const start = page.current * PAGE_SIZE;
    const end = start + PAGE_SIZE;

    const nextItems = allData.slice(start, end);

    setItems(prev => [...prev, ...nextItems]);
    page.current += 1;
  };

  useEffect(() => {
    // initial load
    loadMore();
  }, []);

  const handleScroll = () => {
    const { scrollTop, clientHeight, scrollHeight } =
      document.documentElement;

    if (scrollTop + clientHeight >= scrollHeight - 100) {
      loadMore();
    }
  };

  const throttledScroll = useRef(
    throttle(handleScroll, 300)
  ).current;

  useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener("scroll", throttledScroll);

    return () => {
      window.removeEventListener("scroll", throttledScroll);
      throttledScroll.cancel();
    };
  }, [throttledScroll]);

  return (
    <div>
      {items.map((item, index) => (
        <div key={index} style={{ padding: 10 }}>
          {item}
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

***

## ✅ Why Throttle (not Debounce) Here?

| Scenario       | Debounce | Throttle |
| -------------- | -------- | -------- |
| Search input   | ✅        | ❌        |
| Scroll loading | ❌        | ✅        |
| Infinite list  | ❌        | ✅        |
| Resize         | ✅        | ✅        |

### ❌ Debounce would wait until scrolling stops

### ✅ Throttle loads data **while user is scrolling**

***

## ✅ But ⚠️ IMPORTANT: Throttle Alone Is NOT Enough

### 🚨 Rendering 1 lakh DOM nodes is still BAD

You should combine throttle with:

### ✅ 1️⃣ Pagination / Incremental Loading ✅ (you already do this)

### ✅ 2️⃣ Virtualization (VERY IMPORTANT for large lists)

***

## ✅ BEST Solution (Real‑World Apps)

### ✅ Use:

*   **Throttle** → control scroll handling
*   **React‑Window / React‑Virtualized** → render only visible items

```bash
npm install react-window
```

***

### ✅ Example with Virtualization (Recommended)

```jsx
import { FixedSizeList as List } from "react-window";

<List
  height={600}
  itemCount={100000}
  itemSize={35}
  width="100%"
>
  {({ index, style }) => (
    <div style={style}>Item {index + 1}</div>
  )}
</List>
```

✅ Only **20–30 DOM nodes exist at any time**  
✅ Even 1 lakh records → buttery smooth

***

## ✅ Interview‑Ready Answer

> **Yes, throttle helps in infinite scrolling by limiting how often the scroll handler executes. It ensures that loading the next 30–40 records happens at controlled intervals. However, for large datasets like 1 lakh records, throttle should be combined with pagination and virtualization to avoid performance issues.**

***

## ✅ One‑Line Version (Very Important)

**“Throttle controls scroll event frequency, not rendering. It must be combined with incremental loading or virtualization for large datasets.”**

***

## ✅ Final Recommendation (Industry-Level)

✅ Use **Throttle** for scroll  
✅ Load **30–40 records at a time**  
✅ Use **React Window** for virtualization  
✅ Never render all records at once

